ION","url":null,"node_id":"MDc6TGljZW5zZTA="},"allow_forking":true,"is_template":false,"web_commit_signoff_required":false,"topics":["background-jobs","jobs","ruby","sidekiq"],"visibility":"public","forks":2471,"open_issues":40,"watchers":13447,"default_branch":"main","permissions":{"admin":false,"maintain":false,"push":false,"triage":false,"pull":true}},"body":"Ruby version: 3.2.2\r\nRails version: 7.0.8\r\nSidekiq / Pro / Enterprise version(s): 7.1.6\r\n\r\n[This change](https://github.com/sidekiq/sidekiq/commit/e9f212902185591831af514df6313f8ae2cce31a#diff-8360e8f6436eec9d748f97a72a62912bf00588fd427672d5b1e65f03e401a456R19) breaks a scenario like this:\r\n\r\n```ruby\r\nSidekiq::Testing.inline! do\r\n  Job1.perform_async # mode is inline\r\n\r\n  Job2.perform_async # mode is now fake (it's nil, and fake is default)\r\nend\r\n\r\nclass Job1\r\n  def perform\r\n    Rails.env.test? ? Sidekiq::Testing.fake! { reschedule_in_the_future } : reschedule_in_the_future\r\n  end\r\nend\r\n```\r\n\r\nIt's (simplified) what we use to avoid infinite loops with `perform_in` with inline testing. Perhaps a mention in the changelog would be good, because blocks don't work as they used to now, unless you can reconcile it with thread-safety. I'll be adapting tests to avoid this (use global mode `inline` instead of the first block).\r\n\r\nUpdate: Also, jobs pushed in `Sidekiq::Batch` now execute after the jobs block, even in inline mode, which again breaks some mocking.","reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sidekiq/sidekiq/issues/6072/reactions","total_count":0,"+1":0,"-1":0,"laugh":0,"hooray":0,"confused":0,"heart":0,"rocket":0,"eyes":0},"timeline_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sidekiq/sidekiq/issues/6072/timeline","performed_via_github_app":null,"state_reason":"completed"}},"event":"cross-referenced"},{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sidekiq/sidekiq/issues/comments/1794062414","html_url":"https://github.com/sidekiq/sidekiq/issues/6069#issuecomment-1794062414","i